         <abstract>
            <p>The task of the portfolio manager is to assemble the package of securities that promises the highest expected return consistent with maximum allowable risk. The key to determining how actively a portfolio manager should trade in attempting individual stock selection and market timing is the quality of the return forecasts available to him. The so-called "random walk" theory implies that these forecasts will be worthless. In the author's study, however, eight analysts covering some 250 common stocks demonstrated a significant degree of forecasting success, with the bulk of the confirming price change occurring within one month.</p>
          </abstract>
